1. Test Matrices for Different Environments, Node Versions, and OS
    - You want to make sure your Node.js app works across multiple combinations of:
    - Node.js versions (e.g., 16, 18, 20)
    - Operating systems (e.g., Linux, macOS, Windows)
    - Environment variables or configurations (e.g., development, staging, production)
    - Example using GitHub Actions:
        name: Node.js CI
        on:
            push:
                branches: [main]
            pull_request:
                branches: [main]
        jobs:
            test-matrix:
                runs-on: ${{ matrix.os }}
                strategy:
                    matrix:
                        os: [ubuntu-latest, windows-latest, macos-latest]
                        node: [16, 18, 20]
                steps:
                - uses: actions/checkout@v3
                - name: Setup Node.js
                    uses: actions/setup-node@v3
                    with:
                        node-version: ${{ matrix.node }}
                - name: Install dependencies
                    run: npm install
                - name: Run tests
                    run: npm test
    - Explanation:
        - This runs the test suite across all Node.js versions and OS combinations, ensuring broad compatibility.
        - Any failure indicates a platform-specific issue.

2. Integration and End-to-End Tests as Pipeline Stages:
    - Integration tests: Test multiple modules working together.
    - End-to-end (E2E) tests: Test the full app workflow (e.g., API + DB + UI).
    - Example pipeline stages (GitHub Actions, Node.js app):
        jobs:
            integration-tests:
                runs-on: ubuntu-latest
                steps:
                    - uses: actions/checkout@v3
                    - uses: actions/setup-node@v3
                        with:
                        node-version: 18
                    - run: npm install
                    - run: npm run test:integration   # e.g., tests with database
                    - run: npm run test:e2e           # full workflow tests
    - Explanation:
        - You can split unit, integration, and E2E tests into separate stages.
        - Each stage can fail independently, helping isolate problems.

3. Automated Test Coverage Reports and Quality Gates (SonarQube):
    - Test coverage: Shows what percent of your code is tested.
    - Quality gates: Rules like “coverage must be ≥80%” or “no new critical code smells” before merging code.
    - Steps for Node.js + SonarQube:
        - Install coverage tool (e.g., Jest + jest --coverage):
            {
                "scripts": {
                    "test": "jest",
                    "test:coverage": "jest --coverage"
                }
            }
        - Run coverage in CI:
            - name: Run tests with coverage
            run: npm run test:coverage
        - Upload to SonarQube:
            - name: SonarQube Scan
            uses: SonarSource/sonarcloud-github-action@master
            with:
                projectKey: my-node-app
                organization: my-org
                token: ${{ secrets.SONAR_TOKEN }}
    - Explanation:
        - SonarQube checks coverage, code smells, duplications, vulnerabilities.
        - You can fail the pipeline if quality gates are not met, enforcing high code standards automatically.